Consecutive convolutions:We can chain two, or more, convolutions into a single TN diagram (Figure B14) to obtain a deep linear CNN [65] similar to deep linear networks which are popular for analytical studies.

Convolution weight/input JVPs:In the main text, we derived the Jacobians of convolution (SS3.1) which can be used to derive the JVPs. A JVP propagates perturbations \(\mathbf{V}^{(\mathbf{W})}\in\mathbb{R}^{C_{\text{out}}\times C_{\text{in}}\times K_{1 }\times K_{2}}\) and \(\mathbf{V}^{(\mathbf{\mathbb{X}})}\in\mathbb{R}^{C_{\text{in}}\times I_{1}\times I_{2}}\) in the input space to perturbations in the output space by contracting the perturbation with the Jacobian. See Table B3 for the general einsun expressions.

